column2: my name's Harry and I just graduated with a degree in mathematics. I struggled with math growing up. This gives me a unique perspective on what makes math so difficult for so many people.

column1: **My hypothesis for why math is so hard for students:**
Math is difficult because it is abstract. Our thoughts are typically concerned with concrete things like dogs
column5: etc. Concrete things don't start off being easy
column6: but over time we come to understand them through experience and with the help of mental models. Mathematical concepts on the other hand are abstract and don't often appear in the real world directly
column7: which makes it difficult for us to form models of them in our minds (ex. when you last encountered a negative number directly?). The goal of mathematical education is to help students become familiar with these new types of objects
column8: and many of the failings the Canadian math curriculum come down to its assumption that everyone learns to use and represent these objects in the same way.

column1: **My solution for making math easier for students:**
I don't assume how a student thinks. Instead
column2: I give my students a concrete problem to solve
column3: without telling them what math to use. When the student has successfully solved the problem
column4: I ask them if they can draw any lessons from their solution. I then modify the problem
column5: adding a layer of abstraction. The student tries again to solve this new problem
column6: but with the aid of any techniques they've developed so far. As we work through these problems in this way
column7: the student builds a mental representation of the mathematical processes as well as concepts used to solve a particular set of problems. We use this representation to discuss how the student's understanding of the problem relates to what they're doing in class and the official ""terms and definitions"" for the various methods and concepts they developed on their own. This method is inspired by mathematical education research currently being carried out in the Netherlands. I have seen first hand how effective this technique is. It is also what a lot of ""math-tutoring"" businesses use
column8: though sometimes to a less effective degree (b/c often instructors are not trained on the various techniques and these businesses instead rely heavily on their curriculum to make up for it).

column1: Over many years I've learned better
column2: more intuitive ways of looking at many traditionally challenging math concepts. Fortunately for me
column3: this perspective helped me develop more general ways of approaching my math classes that didn't require me to start from scratch each time. I found that once these foundational skills were formed
column4: the rest was a matter of building more subject-specific tools on top. So
